This is my opinion:<br>
<br>
I don't like &quot;farmers&quot;.  And by farming, I mean the players who camp a much lower-level spawn repeatedly because the mob drops a unique item that sells to PCs for good plat, AND, the player refuses to leave when a lower-level group comes along.<br>
<br>
I can understand a player's &quot;right&quot; to equip their character with the best items to improve their survivability and advance further in the game.<br>
<br>
But I believe that they cross the line when they don't need the item itself ... they just want to sell it for more plat or for bartering.<br>
<br>
The game has very limited resources, and has absurd random drop rates for items that seem to be &quot;necessary&quot; for higher level play.  If we, the players, are to be forced to share those resources, it behooves us to share them efficiently.<br>
<br>
A level 40 shaman farming a level 20 spawn is not as efficient as a group of level 25 characters camping the level 20 spawn.  The lower level group gain both exp and items, the high level player is better off gaining more exp elsewhere.<br>
<br>
That is why I like TLC.  And I hope they iron out the inconsistencies with quest items.<br>
<br>
This is my opinion.  You are entitled to a different one.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uhecateenthroned.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Hecate Enthroned</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/27/01 2:25:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=740.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> TLC</span><hr size=1> I like the challenging aspects that TLC brings to the game, but at the same time detest its implementation and the repercusions it brings with it.<br>
<br>
The TLC is supposedly used to enforce a stricter sense of RP'ing in this server. But in reality all it seems to reward are people with multiple accounts (then you can afford to have that lil newbie around to loot a half dead mob that's been mem blurred, even though I'm not even sure if this &quot;bug&quot; has been fixed) or those that rely heavily on spoiler sites. <br>
<br>
Reading Restorias post for example, she makes mention of how she's a seasoned player and therefore already knew what to get, where to get it and how to get it. In effect TLC doesn't make the game any more real it just adds those extra hurdles that make you feel that much more powerful after having surpassed them. <br>
<br>
As far as RP'ing is concerned, TLC is the most horrid abomination I've seen. You run around in fear of leveling, of surpassing the deadlines set forth by the TLC and exploration and adventuring are discouraged. I think this is in no small part why people complain about seeing little role-playing at times. Everyone with half a clue, knows they'd better start collecting pieces of their epic (clerics for example need to start at level 30 or so), or meeting other quest requirements that might be pre-reqs for future quests. <br>
<br>
In addition, new quests added will be wholly out of the reach of the high level players. If epic quests were to have been implemented with TLC on, none of the high level players in any server would have really been able to get their epics on their own. Instead they'd probably have to pay newbies thousands of plats for items they were theoretically supposed to gather themselves. If for some reason you mess up along the way or there's a bug in the quest, you'll be forced to dish out the plat again. It's really starting to look like fun now.<br>
<br>
In addition, like the concern I posted earlier, loot tables have been tweaked with full server populations in mind, not with a fluctuating level restricted population in mind. Quests will be ALOT harder to complete thanks to mob spawn rarity and drop rarity. In addition, different levels in mob PH's will lead to further discrimination against players trying to complete various quests. So basically, our server drops (except for the high end drops) are going to be terribly skewed and low. <br>
<br>
I hear many of you applauding the TLC because it screws over phat lewt dr00ds/d00dz. WHATEVER. You're so delluded by your hatred for those players that you can't see that TLC favors THEM and uber/power gamers over anybody else. <br>
<br>
Let me illustrate, I've seen druids solo to level 60 in startup servers with minimal and I mean MINIMAL equipment faster than any other player. And at level 60 NOTHING will go Trivial on you, and you have the BEST loot available to you. So you'll just go about and camp the best loot you can camp, which at level 60 is any mob level 45+ (maybe even less with light blue exp in mind). So basically, you're better off saying &quot;screw the mid-level game&quot; and zerg rushing to the 50's where not only is your TLC range larger, as your blue /con range increases by level, but you'll also have better loot optoins available to you. <br>
<br>
Take for example, Restorias example, regarding camping the Frenzied Ghoul for fear it might go TLC. You'd have to be level 56+ for the Frenzied Ghoul to go TLC on you (maybe even higher with light blue exp now in). Hell, I've solo'ed his spawn with a level 50 necro when some guildmates needed FBSS'. So, like I said the TLC doesn't prevent camping and it definitely doesn't screw over the phat lewtz people. <br>
<br>
Some people claim for example that the lower level people will benefit because they'll be able to sell prized items to higher level people. Two big problems with this. It's A PAIN to try and sell anything on this server. Especially in an RP fashion: High_elf01 &quot;here mr necro, here's the piece you needed to complete your necro epic&quot; Yeah.... lots of RP going on there. Plus like Ifirin(sp?) pointed out with no /shout or /ooc it's hella hard to recruit people to help you out with quests. It's guild or bust (or have tons of luck). The second problem is that big guilds will really have no need for anyone's aide, and will be quite capable of camping items regardless of TLC for their members. ie, you need 4 cleric epics, well you just set up a group, PL a char to the appropiate level, clear the spawn of PH'ers, kill the mob with the make believe char, trade to he cleric in the guild that needs it, repeat until you get the four items, and you're set. And trust me PL'ing will probably be easier (you can get level 40 in less than a day if done properly), than trying to enlist the help of players. Because let's face it most encounters of this sort will require a group, not just one character who is within TLC. So not only do you have to convince one person, but you'll have to convince of group of these players and PAY them all to do your biding. Either that or hope players will be guided by greed to the point that they'll want to do these camps on their own. Yet the vast majority of people who are in it for these types of monetary gain are the same people who TLC discourages from joining the server in the first place! <br>
<br>
I've no problem with a challenge, TLC is just not a challenge in my eyes, it's this convoluted horrible abomination of a solution that's been unleashed in an attempt to prevent farming and twinking in what's supposed to be a role-playing environment. And it's failed to do its task as far as I'm concerned. The one character rule has had a stronger effect on that.<br>
<br>
Yet people still support it despite its obvious flaws if only for the reason that d00dz don't like it. It seems all too analogous to driving nails into your skull because it will keep the people you don't like from being around you, nevermind that you'll now have nails in your skull. <br>
<br>
I mean the longer I spend on FV, the crazier devout RP'ers seem. It's like they must make RP'ing into this painfully convoluted process that only a few may engage upon, and is only available to a select few. When newbies inquire about wanting to play on a role-playing server on Verant's TNZ, I have to guide them away from the FV server because they'll be so baffled, frustrated and confused, they'll probably quit the game outright. There actually was a post from what seemed to be a nice girl who was about to give up on the game because of the tragic experiences she'd had while starting out her first character in FV, and if I remember correctly there was not a single post encouraging her to stay in FV because everyone just to accept it was not a viable solution. Is this the type of environment that fosters RP'ing, one that's so hostile and elitist that new players have to be turned away? I  mean how's this server supposed to prosper if only after we've reached higher levels in other servers we can come and play here? <br>
<br>
No wonder in the other servers people sometimes laugh and hold disdain for RP'ing, especially if that's the way it's going to be. <br>
<br>
I've RP'ed most of my EQ life, so don't get me wrong here. I mean to the point that I would walk into Nektulos forest and RP'ing newbies would gather around my character and ask me about tales they heard about me from their guild leaders. And we'd sit around and talk and I' teach them things as if I was some experienced veteran instructing the troops of tomorrow. So don't think I dislike RP'ing, to the contrary, I'm just becoming terribly concerned with how it's been kept away from the public. <br>
<br>
But role-playing is intrinsically a SOCIAL activity, it's something you do between people/players/characters, you need others to role-play, otherwise, does a character even have a story if nobody has heard it? Yet the low population numbers seem of little concern... &quot;oh good, least there's no d00dz&quot;. It's like being in a twilight zone episode, where everyone is just talking to themselves and somehow think that's a perfectly fine way of socializing. It's like holding a LARP with yourself! =P<br>
<br>
And this whole none-sense of &quot;/tells aren't RP&quot;, &quot;Call it seasons, not level&quot;, &quot;Levelling is anti-RP&quot;, &quot;Twinking is anti-RP&quot;, &quot;Grouping is anti-RP&quot;, &quot;Communicating with others in the game is anti-RP&quot;, &quot;making life impossible for ourselves so no one will be around to taunt us is RP&quot;, /boggle <br>
<br>
Maybe the solitude is getting to me in FV, but I've gone from a Love relationship to a strong Love/Hate one, maybe even insanity :P<br>
<br>
(I'm afraid this might be viewed as a flame, but I've spent too much time writing it up, so I'm just going to post it anyways, so don't take it as one, it wasn't meant as a flame :P ) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ustormtower.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stormtower</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 130<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(11/27/01 3:25:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=740.topic&index=30>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: TLC</span><hr size=1> wow Hecate... that was rather long.  Good points, tho.<br>
<br>
I can't say I fully agree with you.<br>
<br>
But I do agree that the way TLC stands right now is really bad: ... with the super-large exp range that high level people have ... and the badly designed quests.<br>
<br>
It is unfortunate that a lot of newbies may be shunted to the FV server to face this stringent ruleset.<br>
