<br>
Do quests add to the immersiveness of the game?  Somewhat, but the fact is most people do not have the patience to spend hours completing a quest that yields nothing satisfying in the way of material rewards.  I'll do simple quests that are &quot;on my way&quot; or that only require a couple hours worth of work, but if a quest is going to take me multiple hours of dedicated effort, I'm sorry, but there are better ways I could be spending my time, like roleplaying with living breathing characters instead of static, scripted NPCs.<br>
<br>
The idea of farming is repellant to me and I applaud Verant for making some effort to make farming a bit more difficult.  I know TLC isn't perfect, largely due to the fact that range of mobs you can gain experience from at higher levels is so large, and the fact that you can use tactics to get around TLC (the mem blurring technique described).  I still think that instead of throwing out the entire idea of TLC, we should take the sensible criticism of TLC and adjust the system so it is more likely to do what it is supposed to.  Instead of making whether or not a person gains experience from a mob the detrimenant, make it so at higher levels the range is manually set, so it is somewhat smaller.  I'm not sure what can be done to prevent the memblur technique, but perhaps someone more knowledgable and creative than I could come up with something.<br>
<br>
